column13:
This dataset provides a university-wide enrollment snapshot (Fall 2020–Fall 2024), broken down by School, Department, Program, Concentration, and Credential type. Each row includes official state (OHE) and federal (CIP) program codes, with N indicating headcount for each term.

Key abbreviations (credentials):

BA/BS = Bachelor of Arts/Science • BS-Teach = Bachelor’s program for teacher preparation

MA/MS/MBA/MSN/MSW = master’s degrees (e.g., Master of Arts, Science, Business, Nursing, Social Work)

ED.D = Doctor of Education • DNAP = Doctor of Nurse Anesthesia Practice

GRADCERT = Graduate Certificate • OCP = Official Certificate Program

SYC = Sixth-Year Certificate • PM CERT = Post-Master’s Certificate

Overall trends (Fall 2020 ? Fall 2024):

Total enrollment declined slightly from 10,652 (2020) to 9,997 (2024), with a low point in 2022 (9,468).

Arts & Social Sciences shrank from 2,970 ? 2,525, with losses in English, Economics, and Journalism, though Criminology and Psychological Science remain large.

Business fluctuated but remained strong (1,874 ? 1,722), with Finance, Marketing, and Accounting trending downward, while MIS and new joint programs (e.g., Business Analytics) expanded.

Education declined (962 ? 795), particularly in Elementary and Special Education teacher-prep pipelines, though graduate credentials (Ed Leadership SYC, Ed.D tracks) remain robust.

Health & Rehabilitation Sciences grew significantly (1,307 ? 1,514), driven by Nursing (BSN, 232?479), Counselor Education, and advanced practice degrees (DNAP).

Engineering, Science & Technology stabilized after a dip (2,895 ? 2,763), with strong growth in Computer Science, Cybersecurity, Data Science (MS), and Mechanical/Construction Engineering, while traditional sciences (Biology, Chemistry, Physics) declined.

No School/Inter-School programs (e.g., Non-Matriculated UG, Exchange, Undecided) rose, especially in Non-Matriculated UG (190?338).
